% Complete Working Example: Python FastAPI Backend Application
% This is a verified, working example that passes pdd sync validation.
% Use this as a reference when generating architecture.json and .pddrc for Python/Go backend projects.
% This example uses TEMPLATE-BASED GROUP CONTEXTS (Strategy B).

% ============================================================================
% PROJECT OVERVIEW
% ============================================================================

A Python FastAPI backend project with:
- SQLAlchemy for database (PostgreSQL)
- Pydantic for request/response schemas
- Python throughout
- REST API with routers

% ============================================================================
% WHY TEMPLATE-BASED GROUP CONTEXTS?
% ============================================================================

In this project, output filenames DERIVE from the basename:
- basename `crm_models` → filepath `backend/crm_models.py`
- basename `crm_schemas` → filepath `backend/crm_schemas.py`
- basename `auth_service` → filepath `backend/auth_service.py`

Because all modules follow the pattern `{directory}/{name}.{ext}`, we use a SINGLE
group context with template placeholders instead of one context per module.

This is the OPPOSITE of Next.js where `home_page` → `app/page.tsx` (no derivation).

% ============================================================================
% ARCHITECTURE.JSON (VERIFIED WORKING)
% ============================================================================

```json
[
  {
    "reason": "SQLAlchemy models define database tables for CRM entities",
    "description": "Database models using SQLAlchemy ORM with Customer, Contact, Deal, and Activity tables.",
    "dependencies": [],
    "priority": 1,
    "filename": "crm_models_Python.prompt",
    "filepath": "backend/crm_models.py",
    "tags": ["database", "models"],
    "interface": {
      "type": "module",
      "module": {
        "functions": [
          {"name": "Customer", "signature": "class Customer(Base)", "returns": "SQLAlchemy model"},
          {"name": "Deal", "signature": "class Deal(Base)", "returns": "SQLAlchemy model"}
        ]
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "reason": "Pydantic schemas for request/response validation",
